05595nam a22006975i 9781782041030DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820410307 a10.1515/97817820410302doi  a(DE-B1597)676628  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPR9390.9.M3bZ86 2013 7aLIT0040102bisacsh04a828.0922300aReading Marechera /ced. by Grant Hamilton.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2013] 1bJames Currey, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b1 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIntroduction: Marechera & the Outside -- t1 A Brotherhood of Misfits: The Literary Anarchism of Dambudzo Marechera & Percy Bysshe Shelley -- t2 Blowing People’s Minds: Anarchist Thought in Dambudzo Marechera’s Mindblast -- t3 Grotesque Intimacies: Embodiment & the Spirit of Violence in ‘House of Hunger’ -- t4 Tracing the Stain in Marechera’s ‘House of Hunger -- t5 Menippean Marechera -- t6 Black, But Not Fanon: Reading The Black Insider -- t7 The Avant-Garde Power of Black Sunlight: Radical Recontextualizations of Marechera from Darius James to China Miéville -- t8 Classical Allusion in Marechera’s Prose Works -- t9 Revisiting ‘The Servants’ Ball’ -- t10 Marechera, the Tree-Poem-Artifact -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVariously understood as literary genius and enfant terrible of African literature, Dambudzo Marechera's work as novelist, poet, playwright and essayist is discussed here in relation to other free-thinking writers.Considered one of Africa's most innovative and subversive writers, the Zimbabwean novelist, poet, playwright and essayist Dambudzo Marechera is read today as a significant voice in contemporary world literature. Marechera wrote ceaselessly against the status quo, against unqualified ideas, against expectation. He was an intellectual outsider who found comfort only in the company of other free-thinking writers - Shelley, Bakhtin, Apuleius, Fanon, Dostoyevsky, Tutuola. It is this universe of literary thought that one can see written into the fiction of Marechera that this collection of essays sets out to interrogate. In this important and timely contribution to African literarystudies, Grant Hamilton has gathered together essays of world-renowned, established, and young academics from Africa, Europe, Asia and Australia in order to discuss the important literary and philosophical influences that course through Marechera's prose, poetry and drama. From classical allusion to the political philosophy of anarchism, this collection of new research on Marechera's work makes clear the extraordinary breadth and quality of thought that Marechera brought to his writing. Grant Hamilton is Assistant Professor of English Literature at the Chinese University of Hong Kong. He is the author of On Representation: Deleuze and Coetzee on the Colonized Subject (Rodopi, 2011), as well as a number of articles on contemporary African, postcolonial, and world literatures. He is currently working on his second book, Deleuze and African Literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnarchism in literature. 0aZimbabwean literature (English)xHistory and criticism. 4aAfrican Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh  aAfrican Literature.  aAnarchism.  aDambudzo Marechera.  aFree-thinking Writers.  aLiterary Genius.  aLiterary Thought.  aPhilosophy.1 aAshcroft, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChirere, Memory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Grant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo